Desert Ecology

For this assignment, we are going to use a modified data set on desert ecology. The data are from: S. K. Morgan Ernest, Thomas J. Valone, and James H. Brown. 2009. Long-term monitoring and experimental manipulation of a Chihuahuan Desert ecosystem near Portal, Arizona, USA. Ecology 90:1708.

  1. For the taxa included in the study, use the fill option to show the proportion of individuals sampled by plot_type.
deserts %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = taxa, fill = plot_type)) + geom_bar() +
  coord_flip() + scale_y_log10()+
  labs(title = "Observations by Taxa",
       x = "Taxa",
       fill = "Plot Type")

  1. What is the range of weight for each species included in the study? Remove any observations of weight that are NA so they do not show up in the plot.
deserts %>% 
  filter(weight!= "NA") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(species,weight), y=weight))+geom_boxplot()+scale_y_log10()+coord_flip()+
  labs(title = "Observation of Weight by Species", x= "Species", y="Weight")

  1. Add another layer to your answer from #5 using geom_point to get an idea of how many measurements were taken for each species.
deserts %>% 
  filter(weight!= "NA") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(species,weight), y=weight))+geom_boxplot()+scale_y_log10()+geom_point(size=0.15)+coord_flip()+
  labs(title = "Observation of Weight by Species", x= "Species", y="Weight")

  1. Which two species have, on average, the highest weight? Once you have identified them, make a new column that is a ratio of weight to hindfoot_length. Make a plot that shows the range of this new ratio and fill by sex.
deserts %>% 
  group_by(species) %>% 
  filter(weight!= "NA") %>% 
  summarise(avg_weight=mean(weight)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(avg_weight))
